---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Disclaimer from '../../components/ui/Disclaimer.astro';
import { publicSiteOrigin } from '../../lib/site/url';

const site = publicSiteOrigin();
const published = '2026-05-05';

const schema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Article',
  headline: 'FI Score and Freedom Timelines',
  datePublished: published,
  dateModified: published,
  author: { '@type': 'Organization', name: 'Yield to Freedom', url: site },
  publisher: { '@type': 'Organization', name: 'Creative Bandit LLC', url: site },
  description: 'How to think about monthly portfolio income versus expense targets on the path to financial independence.',
};
---

<Base
  title="FI Score & timelines — Yield to Freedom"
  description="Map portfolio income to monthly expenses and stress-test what “enough” really means."
  schema={schema}
>
  <article
    class="max-w-3xl space-y-4 leading-relaxed text-slate-700 [&_a]:font-semibold [&_a]:text-blue-700 hover:[&_a]:text-blue-900 [&_ul]:list-disc [&_ul]:space-y-2 [&_ul]:pl-6 [&_strong]:font-semibold"
  >
    <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-slate-900">FI Score & timelines</h1>
    <p>
      Financial independence rarely hinges on one number—you need recurring cash flows (or reliably sellable assets)
      that meet or exceed recurring expenses across realistic stress tests. Yield to Freedom tracks this by comparing
      <strong>durable portfolio income</strong> to your <strong>monthly expense target</strong>.
    </p>
    <h2 class="mt-10 text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">Simple mental model</h2>
    <p>
      If your brokerage projects ~$450 of monthly ETF distributions net of withholding and your lean monthly budget is
      $13,500, you are ~3.3% of the way on an income-only basis—which is why we pair income sleeves with growth and
      stability pillars instead of chasing the highest headline yield in isolation.
    </p>
    <h2 class="mt-10 text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">Why we still show growth sleeves</h2>
    <p>
      Names like <a href="/etfs/VOO">VOO</a> or <a href="/etfs/QQQ">QQQ</a> might trail covered-call funds on raw
      yield, but they anchor long-term purchasing power. The FI timeline is healthier when withdrawals can flex between
      yield, modest sales, and side income rather than pretending distributions alone will never fluctuate.
    </p>
    <h2 class="mt-10 text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">Putting ETFs to work</h2>
    <p>
      Browse income-focused funds such as <a href="/etfs/JEPI">JEPI</a>, <a href="/etfs/SPYI">SPYI</a>, and{' '}
      <a href="/etfs/SCHD">SCHD</a>, blend them deliberately, and record “distribution per $100k invested” in a
      spreadsheet so you stress-test downturns realistically.
    </p>
    <p>
      Also read <a href="/strategy/drip">DRIP mechanics</a> and{' '}
      <a href="/strategy">the strategy overview</a>.
    </p>
    <Disclaimer />
  </article>
</Base>
